ish: habitational name from Crichton, near Edinburgh, first recorded <i>c.</i> 1128 in the form <i>Crectune</i>, in 1287 as <i>Crecton</i>, and in 1360 as <i>Creychtona</i>. The name is probably an early hybrid compound of Old Welsh <i>creic</i> ‘rock’ + Older Scots <i>tun</i> ‘farm, settlement’ (Old English <i>tūn</i>). In Ireland and Britain, this form of the name is now found chiefly in northern Ireland; the more usual Scottish forms are   Crichton   and   Crighton  .","Irish: sometimes used for Gaelic <b>Ó Creacháin</b> or <b>Ó Criocháin</b> (see   Crehan  ).","English: habitational name from Creighton in Staffordshire, named with Celtic <i>creig</i> ‘rock’ + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Crichton was born about 1200, in Pathhead, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Thurston Crichton, was 42 and his mother, Mrs. Thurstone de Crichton, was 39. He had at least 1 son with Mrs Crichton. He died about 1240, in his hometown, at the age of 42."},"et":{"Abt 1200–Abt 1240":"umbes 1200–umbes 1240","1200–1240":"1200–1240","1200–Female":"1200–Surnud","1230–1300":"1230–1300","1160–1212":"1160–1212","1162–Female":"1162–Surnud","Abt 1230":"umbes 1230","Abt 1240":"umb